<H3> <TI>   PLO Envoy Reportedly To Ask for U.S. Financial Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO Envoy Reportedly To Ask for U.S. Financial Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306235194 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 2200 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306235194 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] In the file of the Middle East, the PLO is still 
exerting efforts with Western countries for obtaining financial 
aid, and at the same time prepares itself for a new round of 
talks with Israel which will most certainly be held in Cairo. 
Nabila Khraifia: 
  [Khraifia] [passage omitted] President 'Arafat sent Abu 
al-'Ala [Ahmad Quray], economy minister in the Palestinian 
authority, to Washington to ask for urgent financial aid to 
ensure the running of the self-rule institutions. 
  That was announced in Tunis by a Palestinian official who 
refused to reveal his identity. He also pointed out that the 
lack of money was the main reason for postponing President 
'Arafat's trip to the self-rule areas and the installment of the 
Palestinian government in Jericho. 
  The same source pointed out that the donor countries had 
proposed to offer the PLO last week $ 10 million dollar of the $ 
24 million which they promised on 10 June last, and had raised 
it to $18 million dollar after President Yasir 'Arafat had 
rejected it. 

</TEXT>

