<DOCNO> FBIS4-37801 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes122_r_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Comment on Split in Janata Dal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Comment on Split in Janata Dal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2206161194 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2206161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Janata Dal parliamentary party leader, Mr. 
Sharad Yadav, and Mr. Ram Vilas Paswan, MP, are of the view that 
their party has no president at present. Briefing newsmen in 
New Delhi today, they said that had proposed constitution of a 
steering committee for leading the party. They alleged that 
yesterday's split in the party was aimed at destabilizing the 
Lalu Prasad Yadav government in Bihar. 
  Meanwhile, in Patna, a number of Janata Dal MP's and MLA's 
[Members of Legislative Assembly] at a meeting have expressed 
full faith in the leadership of the chief minister, Mr. Lalu 
Prasad Yadav. The chief minister later told newspersons that 
all the ministers and legislators present in Patna attended the 
meeting. On the contrary, Mr. Nitish Kumar, a member of the 
breakaway Janata Dal claimed in Patna today that 90 percent of 
the party's rank and file supported his group in Bihar. He also 
claimed that a majority of party members in the Rajya Sabha will 
soon join the new group. Another member of the split group, Mr. 
Harikishore Singh, told our correspondent in New Delhi that 
their group would like the president of Janata Dal, Mr. Bommai, 
to cooperate with them for upholding the ideals for which the 
party has always stood for. Mr. Bommai, on the other hand, told 
newspersons in Bangalore that he will reach New Delhi tomorrow 
in a bid to bring back the breakaway group of MP's back into 
party fold. He described the decision by the 14 MP's as 
unfortunate, but not unexpected. Orissa chief minister, Mr. 
Biju Patnaik, told newspersons in Bhubaneshwar that the split 
will not have any impact on the party in Orissa. 
  Reacting on the split of the Janata Dal, the Congress-I 
spokesman, Mr. V.N. Gadgil, told newsmen in New Delhi that it is 
always sad in a democracy when a party splits. But, in the case 
of Janata Dal, it was inevitable. He said the Janata Dal was 
never a homogeneous party with leaders having no following. 
  The BJP [Bharatiya Janata Party] says only those political 
parties which have grown on the basis of an ideology will 
survive. The party spokesperson, Mrs. Sushmaswaraj, said that 
the political which have merged for political convenience will 
break up and disappear. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37802 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes122_r_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao Rules Out Ban on Satellite TV Channels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao Rules Out Ban on Satellite TV Channels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2406094094 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2406094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister, Mr. P.V. Narasimha Rao, has 
called for the involvement of Panchayats [rural bodies] to 
disseminate information about developmental activities. 
Inaugurating the 21st conference of state ministers of 
information and cinematography in New Delhi today, he said 
Panchayat leaders should form part of a vital link in the two 
way communicational structure that should be established. This, 
he said, is very essential as a large number of beneficiaries of 
social welfare schemes are ignorant of them. Drawing attention 
to the revolution that is taking place in the field of 
information technology, Mr. Rao said we should preserve our 
cultural identity to prevent our society from becoming 
directionless. 
  Ruling out banning of satellite television channels, the 
prime minister said that Doordarshan [Indian Television] and All 
India Radio have a lot to learn from foreign media though they 
should not emulate them. He called for more attention to 
developing the programs that will be presented to the people. 
  In his keynote address, the information and broadcasting 
minister, Mr. K.P. Singh Deo, called for better coordination 
between the central and state governments to make mass 
communication more effective. He said his ministry is having a 
fresh look at the composition and terms of inter-media publicity 
coordination committees that are already working at the state 
level. 
  The meeting is discussing in three sessions the subjects of 
entertainment tax and films, interpersonal media, and the 
electronic media. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

