<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Kuwait </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on Ties With Egypt, Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister on Ties With Egypt, Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2406093294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0730 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 24 Jun (MENA) -- Kuwaiti Interior Minister 
Shaykh 'Ali Sabah al-Salim has said there is full cooperation 
and coordination between Egypt and Kuwait on various issues 
concerning the two countries, especially relating to security. 
He noted that there is continuous consultation among officials. 
  In a statement to MENA, he denied any form of extremism or 
terrorism in Kuwait, be it intellectual or ideological. He 
emphasized that everyone has the right to openly state his view 
within the law and general controls. 
  He said security in Kuwait is very stable and that 
everything 
is now under control. He added that most of the negative 
security aspects that emerged after the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait 
have been eliminated. He affirmed that security reports coming 
in from the various sectors indicate that Kuwait now enjoys 
greater security and stability than before. He denied there 
were any human rights violations in Kuwait. 
  He said there are around 180,000 maids from various 
countries 
in Kuwait, who enjoy their full rights. He added that the 
Kuwaiti authorities do not approve of anyone's material or moral 
rights being violated in Kuwait and noted malicious foreign 
media reports trying to damage Kuwait's reputation. 
  He said Kuwait respects and preserves human rights and the 
security and safety of all workers in Kuwait, adding that there 
are around 1 million foreigners from 120 countries working in 
Kuwait and that their rights are respected. 
  Commenting on talk of tension between National Assembly 
deputies and the Kuwaiti Interior Ministry, he said relations 
between ministry officials and the National Assembly are 
proceeding well. He noted that everyone's basic goal is to 
preserve public order and stabilize the situation on every level. 

</TEXT>

