<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Southern Officials Call For Sanctions on Sanaa </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Southern Officials Call For Sanctions on Sanaa </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306220594 Kuwait Radio Kuwait in Arabic 2100 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306220594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait Radio Kuwait </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Officials in Aden called on the United Nations to 
impose sanctions on the government of Sanaa to lift the siege it 
was imposing on Aden. 
  Anis Yahiya, head of the south Yemeni delegation touring 
Western Europe and the United States, said in a news conference 
he held in London that the threat of imposing sanctions was the 
only means to stop the northern bombardment of Aden. 
  He added that the sanctions would force Yemeni President 
'Ali 
'Abdullah Salih to comply with UN Security Council Resolution 
No. 924, which called for a cease-fire in Yemen. 
  That came at a time when the intensity of the continued 
northern shelling of Aden and its suburbs had increased. 
  A southern communique affirmed that the northern shelling 
had 
caused the death and wounding of 800 people since 17 June 
instant. [passage omitted] 
  An official in Aden said that the main plant for generating 
electricity was subjected to an aerial and artillery bombardment 
by the northern forces, a matter which led to a power supply cut 
in Aden and caused heavy losses to the plant. 

</TEXT>

