<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Top GCC Official Deplores Fighting in Yemen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Top GCC Official Deplores Fighting in Yemen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106015494 Riyadh SPA in Arabic 2145 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106015494 </F>
<F P=104>  Riyadh SPA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riyadh, 20 June, SPA -- The assistant secretary 
general for political affairs at the Gulf Cooperation Council 
[GCC], ambassador 'Abd-al-Aziz Bu'ali, has stressed the 
anxiousness of their majesties and highnesses the leaders of the 
GCC countries to back any joint Arab action and to sanction Arab 
unity in any part of the Arab homeland, proceeding from their 
belief that any cooperation gives strength to the Arab nation 
and consequently the Muslim nation. 
  At a press conference held today at the GCC headquarters in 
Riyadh, he said: "When Yemen's unity was established in May 1990 
the GCC countries supported and sanctioned this unity which came 
about with mutual consent". 
  He also talked about the great efforts made by the GCC to 
stop the conflict between the brethren in Yemen and find a 
suitable ground to solve the conflict through negotiations and 
away from bloodshed, massacres and destruction. 
  He reviewed the efforts made by the servant of the two holy 
places, King Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz Al Sa'ud, His Highness 
Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan, president of the United 
Arab Emirates, and their brothers the GCC leaders to contain 
this crisis. He then deplored the worsening of the conflict 
between the two sides which led to the destructive war going on 
in Yemen now. He stressed that the fundamental view of the GCC 
states now was to insist on a cease-fire. 
  In reply to a question on the nature of measures which the 
GCC states could take if the fighting continued between the two 
sides, Ambassador Bu'ali said he hoped that fighting would end 
between the two sides, otherwise other steps would have to be 
taken either by the GCC states or the Security Council. He 
added that the goal which the GCC states were pursuing was to 
stop the bloodshed and the destruction. He further said: What 
matters to us now is to stop the fighting and prevent the flames 
of war from spreading here and there, and as for the rest -- 
everything will be examined accordingly and we will deal with 
the developments in the future. 
  In reply to a question on the GCC center for commercial 
arbitration, he indicated that the center was set up to 
arbitrate disputes which might arise between a trader and 
companies or between other traders involved in similar 
commercial activities with the GCC states abroad [as received]. 
Finally, he reviewed the commercial projects which would be 
executed in the framework of cooperation among the GCC states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37839 </DOCNO>
