<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   League Chief on Yemen, Libyan-Western Crisis, Iraq </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    League Chief on Yemen, Libyan-Western Crisis, Iraq </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2206184594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1618 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2206184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 22 Jun (MENA) -- Arab League Secretary 
General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid has renewed his call to the 
Yemeni belligerents to abide by the UN Security Council's 
cease-fire resolution to safeguard the lives of the Yemeni 
people and to enter into a constructive dialogue to promote 
security and stability for the fraternal Yemeni people. He 
expressed the Arab League's readiness to do its utmost to 
achieve this goal. 
  In an interview with the weekly magazine AL-MUSAWWAR 
published today, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that the fighting 
between brothers in Yemen has led to divisions and exacerbated 
the crisis. He expressed the hope that the two sides in Yemen 
will resume their dialogue as soon as possible. 
  Asked whether South Yemen has submitted an application to 
the 
Arab League to become an independent member, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid 
said: Yes, it did, but no action has been taken. The 
application is held in the General Secretariat until the Arab 
League Council holds its next meeting. 
  Asked about the internationalization of the Yemeni crisis 
and 
the fact that some states prefer to refer Arab problems to the 
United Nations, the Arab League secretary general pointed out 
that North Yemen was the one that first objected to Arab League 
mediation, because, as the Yemeni officials said, this is an 
internal matter. He said that North Yemen objected not only to 
Arab League mediation but also to UN mediation. 
  Regarding the Libyan-Western crisis and whether Libya has 
accepted the Arab League's proposal to conduct the trial of the 
suspects at the International Court of Justice in The Hague 
according to Scottish law and with Scottish judges, Dr. 
'Abd-al-Majid expressed his thanks to the Libyan leadership for 
accepting this delicate and sensitive political and legal 
situation. He noted in this regard that the recent Nonaligned 
Movement foreign ministers' conference in Cairo supported this 
initiative. He said that contacts have been held with UN 
Security Council member states and the European Union in this 
regard, and the atmosphere is completely suitable for discussing 
the means to achieve a peaceful settlement to this problem. He 
added that this will prevent an escalation of the Libyan-Western 
crisis in August, sparing the area further tension. He noted 
that a number of European countries who have interests in Libya 
do not want an escalation of the crisis and are ready to listen 
to Libya's views on the issue. 
  Regarding the embargo on Iraq, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid expressed 
hopes that the embargo will be lifted and that the Iraqi people 
will enjoy freedom, security, and stability. He said that 
everything is in the hands of the Iraqi Government. It can ask 
the UN Security Council to lift the embargo after it implements 
the UN resolutions, including those concerning recognition of 
Kuwait's sovereignty, the border demarcation, compensation, and 
the prisoners. 
  Regarding Israeli operations in Lebanon, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid 
said that what Israel has done and is doing against Lebanon is 
contrary to peace. He affirmed that Lebanon has the right to 
defend its territory and to demand the withdrawal of the Israeli 
forces. 
  He added that if Israel really wants peace in the area, it 
must stop its actions and embark on serious and effective 
negotiations to avoid operations by the Lebanese resistance, 
which is defending itself and trying to end the occupation. 
This, he said, is a legitimate right that applies to Lebanon, 
Syria, and the Palestinians, just as it applied in the past to 
Egypt before the liberation of its national territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37843 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes123bb_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-al-Majid on Yemeni Crisis, Recognition of South </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abd-al-Majid on Yemeni Crisis, Recognition of South </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2606112594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1055 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 26 Jun (MENA) -- Arab League Secretary 
General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid has called on the Yemeni 
leaders to resolve the situation and stop the fighting 
immediately. He deeply regretted the violation of the 
cease-fire for the sixth time today and reiterated the need to 
implement Security Council Resolution 924 and restore the 
constructive dialogue between the two sides. 
  In statements he made today, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that the 
Yemeni crisis has in fact entered a stage of 
internationalization, with the Security Council's intervention. 
He noted that the Arab League had tried to resolve the crisis, 
but its mission was unsuccessful. 
  He ruled out the possibility of sending an Arab League 
delegation on a new mediation mission to resolve the Yemeni 
crisis. But he referred to possible Arab League participation 
as part of a UN delegation undertaking to arrange a cease-fire 
there. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid went on to say that the Arab League's 
Secretariat General is at present coordinating with the United 
Nations in the search for a solution to the crisis. He added 
that the Arab League does not aim to compete with any other 
party or to exclude anyone from the solution mechanism, but its 
main objective is to reach a cease-fire and search for a 
settlement through a constructive and objective dialogue between 
the Yemeni parties. 
  On the question of the Arab League's recognition of the 
south 
Yemeni state, he said: We in the Arab League are bound by rules 
and laws that stem from the Charter and its council's authority. 
He added: The Arab League accepted the unity of the two Yemeni 
sectors when the north and south were joined into one state that 
became the Yemeni people's legitimate representative. 
  He said that any change in this status requires referral to 
the League's Charter and its council's authority. He expressed 
his belief that the question of recognition is not the only 
issue being raised now. He added that the main issue is the 
cease-fire and the restoration of a dialogue between the Yemeni 
parties. He added that it is premature to raise the question of 
recognizing south Yemen at the Arab League level. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid went on to say that the Arab League member 
states are sovereign. If one of these countries recognizes 
south Yemen unilaterally without the Arab League's involvement, 
the League would have no authority over it. 
  He stressed that the Arab League is constantly coordinating 
with the representatives accredited to it and with the United 
Nations through the League's New York offfice, which is 
constantly sending reports on the latest Yemeni crisis 
developments in the United Nations. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said he expects the Security Council to 
hold another meeting to emphasize the cease-fire resolution. 
But he ruled out a Security Council resolution imposing 
international sanctions on any party that violates it. 
  He admitted that it is difficult for the Arab League to 
adopt 
a resolution on dispatching international observers to supervise 
the cease-fire in Yemen, not only because Sanaa is opposed to 
it, but also because there are technical, administrative, and 
logistical difficulties that impede the international observers' 
work in Yemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

