<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tells Kuwaiti Paper Yemen `Dangerous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tells Kuwaiti Paper Yemen `Dangerous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706092494 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0804 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2706092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 27 Jun (MENA) -- Arab League Secretary 
General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid has described the situation in 
Yemen as dangerous. He said the main reason for the fighting 
between the two parts is that Yemeni unity was not established 
on a sound basis, the armed forces continued to be split into 
two, and there were two different currencies. 
  In a statement to the Kuwaiti newspaper AL-WATAN today he 
regretted the failure of the UN secretary general's envoy 
Lakhdar Brahimi's mission and appealed to leaders of the two 
sides to end the fighting and immediately start negotiations 
under the auspices of the United Nations or any other party they 
agree upon to stem the bloodshed in the country. 
  'Abd-al-Majid emphasized that the Arab League's primary goal 
is to stop the bloody fighting between the two sides. He noted 
that the issue of recognizing south Yemen is left for the 
future, that the League's documents indicate that the Yemeni 
Arab Republic is a unified state, and that any change in status 
should be decided at the League Council in light of the northern 
and southern parties' views. 
  Concluding his statement, 'Abd-al-Majid said unity can never 
be imposed by force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

