<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yemen Given as Reason for Postponement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yemen Given as Reason for Postponement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2606110094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1030 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait, 26 Jun (MENA) -- Responsible sources in the 
Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry have stated that the reason for 
postponing the meeting of the Damascus Declaration countries' 
foreign ministers, which was scheduled to start on Tuesday [28 
June], is these countries' desire to wait for the outcome of the 
UN Security Council decision on Yemen, in addition to the 
foreign ministers' commitments to unforeseen activities. 
  Ambassador Khalid al-Jarallah, director of the Gulf 
Cooperation Council's affairs at the Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry, 
said that consultations are now under way between the Damascus 
Declaration countries' foreign ministers to set a new date for 
the meeting, adding that there is a proposal to hold it next 
week. 
  In an exclusive statement to MENA's correspondent in Kuwait, 
he said that a number of issues will top the agenda of the 
meeting, the most important of which are the situation in Yemen 
in light of the expected Security Council resolution, Iraqi 
intransigence in implementing the UN resolutions, the Middle 
East peace process and its developments, and other issues of 
concern to the member countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

