<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Crisis' Reported Among Top Fatah Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Crisis' Reported Among Top Fatah Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2406144094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 24 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2406144094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Severe Crisis Erupts Among </F>
Traditional Fatah Leaders"] 
  [Text] Tunis, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- While eyes are focused 
on knowing when Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat is going to 
leave Tunis for Gaza and Jericho to assume the self-rule 
authority there, well-informed Palestinian sources have told 
AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that a severe crisis has erupted among the 
main Fatah leaders: Yasir 'Arafat, Mahmud 'Abbas [Abu-Mazin], 
Muhammad Ghunaym (Abu-Mahir), and Faruq Qaddumi [Abu-al-Lutf]. 
  The sources said that Abu-Mahir, head of the Mobilization 
and 
Organization Department [MOD] and member of the Central 
Committee, has decided to quit political action and that he 
intends to reside in Amman or Damascus or remain in Tunis. 
  According to the sources, the Palestinian president, who has 
close social links with Abu-Mahir, tried early in the week to 
persuade him not to resign, but his attempts failed, although 
'Arafat personally visited the MOD head's office last Sunday and 
had lunch with Abu-Mahir the day before yesterday. 
  Other information indicates that Abu-Mazin too has expressed 
to the Palestinian president his wish to quit organizational and 
political action -- which some people have interpreted as 
resignation from Fatah. 
  Meanwhile the new appointments made by 'Arafat have provoked 
angry reactions among numerous Palestinian leaders, especially 
Abu-Mahir, Abu-Mazin, and Abu-al-Lutf. Some circles say that 
they now regard themselves as merely formal leaders in the 
movement and that the ship's helm is now steered by hidden hands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37857 </DOCNO>
