<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Egyptian President Mubarak Arrives for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Egyptian President Mubarak Arrives for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Al-Qadhdhafi Hosts Banquet </H4>

<F P=102> NC2706065394 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0400 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2706065394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Libyan revolution leader Colonel Mu'ammar 
al-Qadhdhafi hosted a banquet last night in honor of President 
Husni Mubarak and his delegation. It was attended by the Libyan 
prime minister, senior Libyan officials, secretaries of the 
General People's Congresses, Egypt's ambassador to the Libyan 
Jamahiriyah, and the Libyan ambassador in Egypt. 
  Talks between President Husni Mubarak and Libyan revolution 
leader Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi opened in the Libyan city 
of Surt last night. President Mubarak and Colonel al-Qadhdhafi 
held a bilateral session of talks followed by an expanded 
session attended by members of the delegation accompanying 
President Mubarak, the secretary of the Libyan General People's 
Committee, ministers, Egypt's ambassador to the Jamahiriyah, and 
Libya's ambassador to Egypt. 
  Information Minister Safwat al-Sharif said the meeting 
between President Mubarak and Colonel Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi 
dealt with several Arab, regional, and world issues. The 
delegates exchanged views on the Yemeni crisis, developments in 
Somalia, and the Middle East issue. The meeting also dealt with 
the general world situation and its political and economic 
impact on Arab and regional issues. 
  Al-Sharif added that the two leaders' talks covered the 
outcome of the African summit held in the Tunisian capital 
recently and the meetings and discussion held on the sidelines 
of the summit. 
  The information minister said the delegates reviewed 
bilateral relations and assessed the implementation of previous 
resolutions passed by the Egyptian-Libyan Higher Joint 
Committee. Within this context the delegates discussed 
implementing a project to build 170 km of railroad between 
Musa'id and Tobruk supervised by a joint working group from the 
Egyptian railroad and Libyan technicians using both countries' 
local resources. Also discussed was a project to lay an oil 
pipeline between Libya and Egypt and an agreement to conduct a 
joint study of the project and set up an Egyptian-Libyan company 
to execute it. 
  The information minister added that the delegates reviewed 
the electrical grid project between the two countries and 
measures taken in this regard as well as bilateral cooperation 
in various sectors, including cultural and media cooperation. 
  President Mubarak and his delegation arrived in the Libyan 
city of Surt last night. They were received by Colonel Mu'ammar 
al- Qadhdhafi and top Libyan officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

