<H3> <TI>   Minister Denies `Defense Camps' Training Foreigners </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Denies `Defense Camps' Training Foreigners </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2406212394 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1500 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA2406212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 24 Jun (SUNA) -- Dr. Husayn Sulayman 
Abu-Salih, the foreign minister, has said that Sudan's foreign 
relations with African, Asian, and neighboring states are stable 
and are developing based on common interests and the 
strengthening of economic and technical cooperation. 
  In an interview published by the Jordanian newspaper AL 
DUSTUR at the end of the 30th summit of African heads of state 
which was quoted by the Sudanese AL INQADH AL-WATANI newspaper, 
Abu-Salih added that Sudan's relations with some Western states 
were better than its relations with Iran. 
  He accused Britain of conveying misleading information on 
Sudan to the United States, which portrayed the people's defense 
camps as places for training foreigners in Sudan. He said we 
still challenge any quarter to prove that a single foreigner has 
completed his training in Sudan. 

</TEXT>

