<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Ummah Party: Government `Harassing' al-Mahdi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Ummah Party: Government `Harassing' al-Mahdi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506202894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1832 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London, 25 Jun (MENA)--The Sudanese opposition 
al-Ummah Party has accused the Sudanese security authorities of 
harassing party leader al-Sadiq al-Mahdi who was arrested last 
Monday. A statement by the party said al-Mahdi and two of his 
aides, who are detained in a Khartoum prison, have suffered 
various harassment acts. Their families are not allowed to 
visit them and they have been denied clean clothes and food from 
outside the prison. 
  The statement added that the Sudanese security authorities 
have barred the lawyers who offered to defend al-Mahdi from 
contacting him and obtaining an indictment against al-Mahdi and 
his colleagues. 
  The statement appealed to human rights organizations and 
fraternal and friendly forces to continue pressuring the 
Sudanese Government to guarantee the safety of and release 
al-Mahdi and his aides immediately. 

</TEXT>

