<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Weak Dollar Expected To Cut Oil Revenues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Weak Dollar Expected To Cut Oil Revenues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506054694 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0345 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2506054694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary prepared by the News Research and Commentaries </F>
Group] 
  [Text] The unprecedented drop in the value of the U.S. 
dollar against the Japanese yen has been coupled with great 
concern in the West's monetary circles, so much so that the 
Japanese foreign minister called on the United States to end the 
joint trade talks by reaching a rapid conclusion and to thus 
mitigate the monetary crisis in the West. 
  Meanwhile, the frightful drop in the value of the dollar 
against the Japanese yen compelled U.S. President Bill Clinton 
to call on the Treasury Department to take immediate steps to 
strengthen the dollar. It should be noted that on Thursday [23 
June] the U.S. dollar sold at less than 100 Japanese yen, which 
is the lowest exchange rate since World War II. The value of 
the dollar against the German mark also dropped to less than 
1.60 German marks to the dollar. 
  International economic experts believe that until 1985, when 
the (Plaza) Accord was implemented to reduce America's trade 
deficit with Japan and Germany and the drop in the value of the 
dollar against European currencies and the Japanese yen were 
taken into consideration, the U.S. dollar was equal to 260 
Japanese yen. This exchange rate has now dropped by more than 
60 percent. 
  The policy of dropping the value of the dollar, which was 
initially started in order to reduce America's trade deficit 
with Japan and Germany, gave rise to hopes that Japan's imports 
would increase while its exports would drop. However, although 
this had negative impacts on Japan, it was unable to correct the 
Tokyo-Washington trade deficit, which is expected to reach $70 
billion this year. 
  Yesterday the central banks of Europe, Japan, and the United 
States intervened in the foreign exchange markets in order to 
strengthen the U.S. dollar; by purchasing dollars, they tried to 
prevent a further drop in its current value. However, Western 
monetary experts are worried that the drop in the exchange rate 
of the U.S. dollar to less than 100 Japanese yen will further 
accelerate the drop in the value of the U.S. currency. Also, 
Wall Street monetary sources believe that although increased 
bank interest rates in the United States may strengthen the 
dollar, it will result in a drop in the price of shares and bond 
rates and that the experience of past economic crises in the 
United States may be repeated. 
  The question now is what impact the drop in the dollar 
against European currencies and the yen will have on the 
countries exporting raw materials, especially oil. Since oil is 
mostly paid for in dollars, and the oil-exporting countries 
import more from Europe and Japan than from the United States, 
the drop in the value of the dollar against the yen and the 
German mark will actually have a negative impact on the regional 
countries' petrodollar purchasing powers. That is why reducing 
oil incomes' dependence on the dollar and diversifying the 
foreign currencies earned from oil exports is being carefully 
considered by the economic experts of the OPEC member countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37886 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes123_s_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-123 </AU>
