<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF Declares Alert in Northern Command Region </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IDF Declares Alert in Northern Command Region </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2606104694 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 26 Jun 94 p A5 </F>
<F P=103> TA2606104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by military correspondent Eytan Rabin] </F>
  [Excerpts] The IDF [Israel Defense Forces] has declared 
alert in its Northern Command and in south Lebanon in 
anticipation of terrorist attacks by Hizballah in the wake of a 
series of IDF operations over the past few weeks. Dozens of 
terrorists were killed in those operations. [passage omitted] 
  Senior Army sources said the IDF continues initiating 
operations against terrorists in south Lebanon. Great 
apprehension prevails among the terrorists, most notably the 
senior ones, who have been sleeping in safe houses away from 
their own homes ever since the abduction of Mustafa al-Dirani. 
  The IDF fears that suicide Hizballah squads will try to 
carry 
out attacks inside the security zone. The attacks may be either 
car bombs or infiltration to Israel through the northern border. 
The IDF has beefed up its patrols in south Lebanon, and troops 
have been instructed to be alert. 
  An SLA [South Lebanese Army] patrol came out unscathed last 
Friday when a powerful bomb exploded as the patrol was moving 
through the western sector last Friday. 
  Army sources have announced that Hizballah's terrorist 
attempts in south Lebanon registered a rise over the past three 
months. One of the sources noted that the recently adopted 
terrorist technique of operating out of houses and the outskirts 
of villages, in which civilian population lives, encumbers the 
IDF activities. In addition to Hizballah's attempts to attack 
the IDF and the SLA, a rise has been noted in similar attempts 
by other bodies, such as Amal and George Habash's organization. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

