<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Chairs `Ministers' First Meeting in Gaza </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th Chairs `Ministers' First Meeting in Gaza </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2606095294 Paris AFP in English 0849 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Gaza City, Gaza Strip, June 26 (AFP) -- Palestinian 
"ministers" held the first meeting of the new authority on the 
Gaza Strip on Sunday [26 June] to review progress in self-rule, 
officials said. 
  International Cooperation and Planning Minister Nabil Sha'th 
chaired the talks at the old Israeli administration building in 
Gaza City. 
  The session was to be followed by a meeting with 
representatives of the World Bank on the disbursement of 
international aid to the Palestinians, who have criticized the 
lack of readily available funds since autonomy was launched on 
May 4. 
  Sha'th, who negotiated the Cairo agreement which launched 
autonomy, said Saturday that Israel and the PLO would resume 
talks on Tuesday on outstanding questions involving self-rule. 
  These would include the size of the self-rule enclave of 
Jericho and the fate of thousands of Palestinian prisoners as 
well as the spreading of autonomy across the West Bank. 
  But the venue for the negotiations has not been settled and 
Israel, which has suggested Cairo, has not officially announced 
any meeting. 
  Among those attending Sunday were West Bank Fatah leader 
Faysal Husayni, Local Government Minister Sa'ib 'Urayqat and 
Tourism Minister Ilyas Frayj. 
  A press conference was due to be held later in the day. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

