<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Welcomes Release of Kidnapped UK Citizens </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Welcomes Release of Kidnapped UK Citizens </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2506155394 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2506155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Islamabad, a spokesman of the Foreign Office has 
welcomed the release of the two British nationals who have been 
kidnapped in Indian-held Kashmir. The Government of Pakistan 
condemns such wanton acts of terrorism, wherever they are 
committed and whosoever is responsible for them. The spokesman 
recalled that the Government of Pakistan had issued several 
public appeals for the release of the kidnapped Britons. Their 
return, safe and unharmed, is a matter of profound relief. The 
spokesman expressed the hope that Britain and other peace-loving 
states would use their influence with India to persuade the 
latter to end its repression in Indian-held Kashmir which is 
undoubtedly responsible for driving the hapless Kashmiris into 
committing such desperate acts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37952 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes123_j_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    North Cuts Coast Road to Aden </H4>

<F P=102> NC2506184794 Paris AFP in English 1820 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, June 25 (AFP) -- Northern Yemeni troops 
cut the coast road between Aden and the oil refinery at Little 
Aden on Saturday [25 June], seriously threatening fuel supplies 
to the city, an AFP correspondent reported. 
  Troops cut the road between the port city and Little Aden, 
18 
kilometres (11 miles) to the west, at the village of Madinat 
al-Sha'b. 
  Southern troops set up a roadblock at the village, which 
lies 
only 10 kilometres (six miles) from Aden, and turned back 
civilian vehicles, saying northern forces were firing at traffic 
on the road. 
  The soldiers said southern troops were trying to push back 
the northern forces. 
  Villagers in Madinat al-Sha'b said the road was cut 
following 
infiltration by northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih. 
  When Aden residents heard of the infiltration long queues of 
cars formed outside the city's petrol stations. 
  If northern forces keep the road cut Aden's fuel supplies 
will be seriously jeopardised because tanker trucks will not be 
able to reach the refinery. 
  A southern military spokesman said earlier Saturday that 
northern forces had launched an offensive towards Madinat 
al-Sha'b. 
  Fierce fighting raged around the village and Aden Radio 
transmitters were hit, forcing the radio off the air. 
  War erupted between Salih's forces and those of his southern 
rival 'Ali Salim al-Bid on May 5. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

