<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Northern Troops Occupy Aden Radio </H4>

<F P=102> NC2606092694 Paris AFP in English 0831 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, June 26 (AFP) -- Northern Yemeni troops 
entered Aden's suburbs, occupying on Sunday [26 June] a power 
station and Radio Aden buildings about 10 kilometres (six miles) 
from the city centre, an AFP correspondent reported. 
  The troops broke through southern defences, heading toward 
the bay of Aden late Saturday. The Hiswah power station and 
Radio Aden are on the coast road. 
  Renewed fighting broke a six-hour calm which fell as Sanaa 
declared a ceasefire from midnight. The truce call was 
immediately rejected by leaders in the breakaway south. 
  Northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih were 
also trying to advance on the Little Aden oil refinery, 18 
kilometres (12 miles) west of the southern stronghold. 
  The south accused the north of taking advantage of a lull in 
fighting to move troops into position for an assault on the 
refinery. 
  Radio Aden stopped all broadcasts late Saturday before the 
northern troops arrived. They were camping out among the 
transmitters on Sunday. 
  They were also installed in the Hiswah power station which 
was put out of action three days ago when a fire broke out there 
after a raid by northern warplanes. 
  Queues of cars formed at Aden petrol stations only to find 
that tanker trucks had been unable to get through roadblocks 
barring the route to the refinery. 
  Civil war broke out in Yemen on May 5 after rival leaders 
failed to resolve differences over running the country. Former 
tribal, conservative North and Marxist South Yemen merged in May 
1990. 
  The south last month proclaimed itself independent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

