<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Memo Reiterates Support for Yemeni Unity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    French Memo Reiterates Support for Yemeni Unity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2606073994 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
0430 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2606073994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] France has reiterated its clear stand in support of 
Yemeni unity. In a memorandum to the Yemeni government on the 
current crisis, France said that it considers Yemeni unity a 
factor of stability in the region and therefore expressed 
reservations over the secessionist declaration. It noted that 
it is paradoxical for the international community to recognize a 
secession resulting from an armed action, given that the 
Republic of Yemen realized its unity through a democratic 
process, a referendum held in May 1991, and legislative 
elections held on 27 April 1993. 
  The memorandum explained the international organization's 
[as 
heard] position on this issue by saying that if the United 
Nations approves such recognition, France fears that the UN's 
credibility will be affected and it will stand bewildered and 
confused when dealing with certain regional crises that are 
similar to the Yemeni crisis; that is, when certain parties 
declare their own establishment such as the Serb Republic in 
Bosnia in the former Yugoslavia for instance. Moreover, France 
does not harbor any hostility. [sentence as heard] 
  In conclusion, the memorandum affirmed support for UN 
secretary general and his special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi. It 
stressed the urgency of calling on all parties to implement the 
cease-fire as stipulated in UN Resolution 924 and convincing 
these parties to continue the dialogue to find a peaceful 
solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37971 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes123_j_94028" </HT>


