<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aden Oil Stocks Said Enough for Several Weeks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aden Oil Stocks Said Enough for Several Weeks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2606112794 Paris AFP in English 1008 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Aden, Yemen, June 26 (AFP) -- Aden has enough oil 
stocks to last several weeks despite being cut off from its 
refinery, a senior southern Yemeni official said Sunday [26 
June]. 
  "We have lots of oil tanks in Aden," said Muhammad Raji, 
secretary-general of the Oil Ministry of the self-proclaimed 
Yemen Democratic Republic. "The supplies can last several 
weeks." 
  Oil reserves at the Little Aden oil refinery, 18 kilometres 
(12 miles) west of the southern stronghold, were moved to Aden 
after northern warplanes attacked the refinery, causing a major 
fire, Raji told AFP. 
  Northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih were 
trying to advance on the refinery Sunday after cutting the coast 
road west of Aden. 
  Electricity has been rationed in Aden for the past three 
days 
since the city's main power station at al-Hiswah, about 10 
kilometres (six miles) away, was damaged by fire following a 
northern bombardment. 
  Northern troops were occupying the power station Sunday. 
  But Raji said the southern authorities were using two other 
power stations, in the northern suburb of al-Mansurah and Khur 
Maksar, near the airport. They had enough fuel for up to two 
weeks. 
  Queues of cars formed at Aden petrol stations Saturday, but 
tanker trucks were unable to get through roadblocks barring the 
route to the refinery. 
  Raji said the authorities could still bring oil into the 
city 
by sea from the al-Mukalla oil terminal in the Hadhramaut 
region, 700 kilometres (434 miles) east of Aden. 
  "The situation is manageable," he said. 
  Petrol stations had instructions only to fill up vehicles' 
tanks, not jerry cans. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-37990 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes123_j_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    North Troops Keep Up `Blitz' </H4>

<F P=102> NC2406134294 Paris AFP in English 1136 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maher Chmaytelli] </F>
  [Text] Aden, Yemen, June 24 (AFP) -- Four civilians were 
killed and 32 people wounded Friday [24 June] as northern troops 
kept up their blitz of Aden, advancing steadily through southern 
defences. 
  Katyusha rockets slammed into the districts of Khur Maksar 
close to Aden airport, Ma'allah near the port and Shaykh 'Uthman 
in the northern suburbs, killing four people and wounding 28 
others, hospital officials said. 
  In fierce fighting on the northwest front at B'ir Ahmad, 15 
kilometres (nine miles) from Aden, four soldiers were wounded, 
they added. 
  Northern troops, who have kept up a barrage of rockets and 
artillery fire on the southern stronghold for more than a week, 
advanced overnight into the town of Bi'r Ahmad after seizing the 
entrance on Thursday, an AFP correspondent reported. 
  Fighting had died down earlier Friday but southern troops 
were massing armoured cars to launch a counter-offensive on 
their northern rivals loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 
  At least 113 civilians have now been killed and about 400 
wounded since the north unleashed its assault on the city last 
Thursday, according to a toll by hospital officials. 
  Thirty people, mostly civilians, were killed and close to 
150 
wounded on Thursday as rocket and artillery fire rained on the 
city in the fiercest day of shelling so far. 
  In Aden residents still have to queue up at 72 wells for 
water, even though southern authorities have managed to 
reconnect supplies from the main pumping station at Bi'r Nasir, 
close to the northern front, hit by northern fire several days 
ago. 
  International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) officials 
said water supplies were "vulnerable" to contamination. 
  They are helping the city authorities install proper pumps, 
so residents do not throw plastic containers directly into the 
water supply. 
  Both the ICRC and a spokeswoman for Medecins Sans Frontieres 
said there were no signs of any epidemics breaking out in the 
city. 
  By advancing from the northwest, northern troops are hoping 
to cut off Aden from the power station in Hiswah, 10 kilometres 
(six miles) from Aden and the oil refinery at Little Aden, 15 
kilometres (nine miles) from the city. 
  Military sources said the south had inflicted heavy losses 
on 
northern troops at Bi'r Ahmad, where "a large number" had been 
killed, 23 tanks destroyed and another seven captured. 
  The rival troops exchanged artillery fire on all fronts 
round 
the embattled city, but southern warplanes continued taking off 
from the airport, despite the shelling. 
  A military spokesman in the city said two northern missiles 
fired on "economic targets" were blown up by southern 
anti-aircraft fire. 
  Meanwhile, southern leader 'Ali Salim al-Bid was holding 
more 
meetings with tribal leaders in a bid to get them to help repel 
the northern forces. 
  On Thursday southern leaders pleaded for foreign 
intervention 
to break the tightening stranglehold on Aden. 
  They said the north was violating a UN ceasefire call 
adopted 
in a Security Council resolution on June 1. 
  Northern Planning Minister 'Abd-al Karim al-Iryani left 
Sanaa 
Thursday for New York, where he is to meet with UN Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali to discuss the situation in Aden. 
  UN special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi failed to broker a 
ceasefire 
in a 10-day tour of the region. 
  Four ceasefires have collapsed since the war erupted on May 
5, shattering a four-year uneasy union between the former 
tribal, conservative North Yemen and the Marxist South. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

