<F P=100> Arabian Peninsula </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Fighting Around Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Northern Attack Resumes 25 Jun </H4>

<F P=102> NC2506085694 Paris AFP in English 0758 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, June 25 (AFP) -- A night-time calm over 
the city of Aden was shattered early Saturday [25 June] when 
northern troops attacked a suburb, wounding 12 civilians, and a 
southern soldier was killed in fierce frontline fighting. 
  Northern rocket and shell attacks stopped late Friday 
bringing an uneasy calm to the battered city after a day in 
which 14 civilians died and 42 were wounded, hospital officials 
said. 
  But the brief lull in the north's siege ended when the 
northern suburb of Dar-Sa'd, close to the frontline, came under 
attack early Saturday. All 12 casualties came from the 
district, hospital officials said. 
  One soldier was killed and seven others wounded in fighting 
at Bi'r Ahmad, about 15 kilometres (nine miles) northwest of 
Aden, where northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah 
Salih were reported to be advancing on Friday. 
  They had taken the school in the middle of Bi'r Ahmad Friday 
after occupying the entrance to the village on Thursday. 
  Southern reinforcements were sent Friday to Bi'r Ahmad to 
try 
to stop the northern advance which threatens to cut off Aden 
from its refinery at Little Aden, 15 kilometres (nine miles) 
away, and the power station at Hiswah, 10 kilometres (six miles) 
away. 
  A southern military spokesman said in Aden late Friday that 
the north "was continuing its desperate attempt to advance on 
Aden," adding they had "suffered hundreds of dead and wounded 
and lost 12 assault tanks." 
  UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali blamed the north on 
Friday for the bombing of Aden and called on Sanaa leaders to 
declare an immediate ceasefire. 
  Southern leaders have said that 376 civilians have been 
killed in Aden and the surrounding area since June 11 and 861 
wounded, in a toll obtained Friday by AFP. 
  Fighting between Salih's men and those loyal to his southern 
rival 'Ali Salim al-Bid broke out on May 5, ending a four year 
uneasy union between the former tribal, conservative North Yemen 
and the Marxist South. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

