<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   League's UN Delegate on Efforts To End Yemeni War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    League's UN Delegate on Efforts To End Yemeni War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2806064794 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0510 GMT 28 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2806064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Ambassador Mahmud Abu-al-Nasr, the </F>
Arab League's delegate at the United Nations, in New York, by 
Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz, in Cairo; date not given; from the 
"Dialogue From Afar" program -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] In front of me 
is a statement by Arab League Secretary General Dr. 'Ismat 
'Abd-al-Majid saying that the League has exhausted its efforts 
to resolve the Yemeni crisis and end the current fighting 
between the Yemeni people. He also said the Yemeni crisis has 
been internationalized by the Security Council's intervention. 
Should we consider this to be a real failure by the Arab League 
to intervene in the crisis? 
  [Abu-al-Nasr] I do not want to say the situation is a 
failure 
or success, because the efforts are continuing. The Arab League 
and the United Nations have tried. This does not mean the two 
organizations have failed to achieve a cease-fire or that the 
door has been closed to future attempts by the Arab league or 
the United Nations. These efforts are continuing and 
cooperation with the Arab League is also continuing. There are 
constant consultations between the UN and Arab League 
secretaries general to reach a solution. I do not want to get 
into the issue of internationalizing the problem because what 
concerns us now is stopping this tragedy and the Yemeni people's 
suffering. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Should we expect a new intervention by the 
Arab League? 
  [Abu-al-Nasr] If the two parties agree. The issue is now 
being raised at the Security Council and undoubtedly the Arab 
League will cooperate with the Council to urge the parties to 
comply with the resolutions passed in this regard. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

