<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Saudi Arabia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudi, Omani Ministers Discuss Yemen Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saudi, Omani Ministers Discuss Yemen Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2606162094 Paris AFP in English 1533 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2606162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, June 26 (AFP) -- Saudi 
Foreign Minister Prince Sa'ud al-Faysal met a senior Omani 
official here Sunday [26 June] to discuss the conflict in 
neighbouring Yemen, where northern forces launched a new 
intensive bombardment of the southern stronghold of Aden. 
  Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yusuf Bin-'Alawi 
'Abdallah paid a brief visit to Jeddah and held talks with 
Prince Sa'ud, Arab diplomats said, only a day after a senior 
northern Yemeni envoy had visited Oman. 
  Meanwhile fighting raged in the suburbs of Aden, following 
the collapse of the fifth ceasefire to be announced in the 
two-month-old civil war. 
  Oman and Saudi Arabia played a key role in securing the 
adoption of UN Security Council Resolution 924 of June 1, which 
called for an immediate ceasefire. Oman currently chairs the 
Security Council. 
  On Saturday 'Abd-al-'Aziz 'Abd-al-Ghani, a member of the 
northern Yemeni presidential council, handed a message to Sultan 
Qabus of Oman from Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 
  The northern Yemeni authorities blamed the south for 
violating the latest ceasefire, declared by Sanaa late Saturday. 
It was set for midnight (2100 GMT). 
  "The (southern) rebel outlaws violated the ceasefire and 
continued their aggression against our armed forces in the Aden 
and Hadhramawt provinces," a northern spokesman said. 
  The northern Yemeni cabinet held a special meeting Sunday to 
discuss the ceasefire, Sanaa radio said, but ministers learned 
of the renewed fighting during the meeting. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

