<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Saudi Arabia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Speaks on Arab, World Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Speaks on Arab, World Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706215294 Riyadh SPA in English 1958 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Riyadh SPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jeddah, June 27, SPA -- The second deputy premier, 
minister of defense, aviation and inspector general, Prince 
Sultan Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz presided over the weekly regular 
session of the Council of Ministers at al-Salam palace in Jeddah 
this afternoon. 
  In a statement to Saudi Press Agency, Information Minister 
'Ali al-Sha'ir said Prince Sultan, at the outset of the meeting, 
had briefed the cabinet on the latest Arab and international 
events and reports related to the Yemeni arena. 
  Prince Sultan highlighted also the great role that had been 
undertaken by Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Fahd 
Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz to end the fighting and save the blood of the 
innocent Yemeni brothers. 
  "King Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz, may the Almighty God preserve 
him, is making continuous efforts on Arab and international 
levels for a decisive and firm ceasefire in Yemen," Prince 
Sultan informed the cabinet. 
  Al-Sha'ir said Prince Sa'ud al-Faysal, the foreign minister 
presented a detailed report on the outcome of his recent tour to 
a number of Arab and western countries during the last few days 
and contents of messages he had sent to a number of Arab foreign 
ministers and the outcome of his talks with them. Prince Sa'ud 
also briefed the cabinet on his impressions of the tour. Prince 
Sa'ud said the wise directives of custodian of the two holy 
mosques King Fahd Bin-'Abd-al-'Aziz at the current critical 
circumstances facing the region, necessitate continuous efforts, 
meetings and consultations to be directed with the aim of 
dedication of peace and stability in the region. 
  Al-Sha'ir said the cabinet also reviewed the latest reports 
carried by the media on the deteriorating situation in Somalia, 
Afghanistan and Bosnia. Referring to Somalia, the cabinet 
expressed regret over the latest and sharp escalations in 
fighting in Mogadishu between the conflicting factions for the 
third day running that led to a big number of casualties and the 
loss of lives. It also expressed concern on the sudden 
escalations in air bombardment operations in the western Afghan 
city of Herat. 
  The cabinet also followed the latest developments in the 
Bosnian arena and the efforts being made by commander of the 
Bosnian Army to defend the lives, territories and honour of the 
Bosnian people on all fronts vis-a-vis the unannounced Serbian 
attacks. 
  In this context, al-Sha'ir said, the Saudi Council of 
Ministers appealed to the conflicting parties throughout Arab 
and Islamic worlds to put weapons aside, seek rational and 
amicable solutions for disputes bearing in mind that conflicts 
between brothers would serve no one except their enemies and 
will never be in the best interests of the Arab and Islamic 
nations. 
  "The Kingdom of Saudi Arabia is always looking forward for 
establishment of peace and justice all over the world," 
al-Sha'ir noted. 
  Meanwhile, the cabinet reviewed a number of domestic items 
on 
its agenda and Prince Sultan listened to views and suggestions 
made by the concerned ministers on them. It also opted for the 
necessary procedures on them. 
  The cabinet agreed on the renewal of the commercial and 
economic agreement between the Government of the Kingdom of 
Saudi Arabia and the Lebanese Republic which was concluded in 
1391 AH [27 February 1971] for one more year effective from 
26-1-1415 [5 July 1994]. 
  It endorsed the closing account of the department of 
retirement and pensions for the fiscal year 1411/1412 AH [24 
July 1990 to 13 July 1991] and approved some appointments at 
Grade 14th. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

