<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Zindani Receives British, U.S. Ambassadors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Zindani Receives British, U.S. Ambassadors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2706180894 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2706180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shaykh 'Abd-al-Majid al-Zindani, member of the 
Presidential Council, today received Robert Douglas Gordon, the 
British ambassador to our country. 
  During the meeting, they discussed bilateral ties, as well 
as 
the current situation and the rebels' noncompliance with the 
cease-fire. 
  The member of the Presidential Council explained the efforts 
that were made and the concessions that were offered in order to 
avoid igniting the fire of sedition and how the rebels insisted 
on sparking it and on departing from legitimacy. He asserted 
that the state does not want war and loves peace. However, he 
added: We are keen on maintaining our unity and the 
independence and sovereignty of our country and the continuation 
of shura and democracy and respecting the people's will, 
represented in the 27 April 1993 elections. 
  For his part, the British ambassador expressed satisfaction 
over the Yemeni government's cooperation with Lakhdar Brahimi, 
the envoy of the UN secretary general. He said that Britain 
supports democracy in Yemen and is anxiously awaiting the report 
that will be presented by the international envoy. 
  Afterward, Shaykh 'Abd-al-Majid al-Zindani, member of the 
Presidential Council, received Arthur Hughes, the U.S. 
ambassador in Sanaa. 
  They discussed bilateral ties and ways of enhancing them. 
The brother member of the Presidential Council asserted that 
the state had complied with the cease-fire but that the rebels 
violated it. He added: We are waiting for the U.S. Government 
to explain its position toward this. He pointed out that the 
Yemeni Republic appreciates the concern of the brothers and 
friends not to see more Yemeni bloodshed, noting that the war is 
not an end in itself and that it will leave negative effects. 
He said all countries that care about Yemen should seek to end 
the war by not extending any moral or material support to the 
secessionist rebels and ensuring our Yemeni people's rights as 
noted in the UN Charter, primarily freedom, democracy, justice, 
and independence. 
  For his part, the U.S. ambassador expressed his satisfaction 
with the recent cease-fire decision issued by the state, saying 
he deems this a step toward a complete cease-fire. He said the 
United States had earlier asserted that it does not approve of 
recognizing secession and that it seeks dialogue. He expressed 
his belief that new efforts for reconciliation could be made by 
Lakhdar Brahimi in a new visit to the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

