<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Bid Decree Turns Brewery Into Soft Drinks Factory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Bid Decree Turns Brewery Into Soft Drinks Factory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2706124094 Paris AFP in English 1157 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2706124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, June 27 (AFP) -- Southern Yemeni 
authorities have decided to turn Aden's brewery -- the only one 
in the Arabian peninsula -- into a soft drinks factory. 
  The decision was a reaction to northern war propaganda which 
has tagged southerners "beer drinkers and atheists," Yemeni 
sources said. Alcohol is forbidden by Islam. 
  The brewery conversion, announced by Aden television Monday, 
was also aimed at pleasing conservative Gulf monarchs who have 
looked favourably on the south during the two-month-old civil 
war, the sources said. 
  A special committee chaired by the breakaway south's trade 
and industry "minister" Yahya al-Jifri will supervise the 
brewery's conversion, the television said, quoting a decree by 
"president" 'Ali Salim al-Bid. 
  The brewery in al-Mansurah, a northwest suburb of Aden, was 
opened in 1981 with the help of former East Germany. It employs 
200 people. 
  Before war erupted on May 5 the brewery produced a million 
half-litre bottles of beer a month under the trademark Seera. 
Water shortages brought production to a halt at least two weeks 
ago. 
  In 1993 the brewery made a net profit of 100 million Yemeni 
riyals, more than eight million US dollars on the official 
exchange rate. 
  The south declared the breakaway Yemen Democratic Republic 
on 
May 21, two weeks after war broke out between al-Bid's forces 
and northern troops loyal to President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-38027 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes124_j_94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
