<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fierce Battles Continue to Rage Near Aden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fierce Battles Continue to Rage Near Aden </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Casualties, Artillery `Duels' Detailed </H4>

<F P=102> NC2806060694 Paris AFP in English 2251 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2806060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Aden, June 28 (AFP) -- Northern Yemeni gunners 
blasted the beleaguered southern capital Aden Monday [27 June], 
killing at least 19 people and wounding 180, hospital sources 
said. 
  Units from both north and south Yemen were locked in 
intensive artillery duels around Madinat al-Sha'b, 10 kilometres 
(six miles) west of Aden city centre, where northern forces 
broke through on Saturday. 
  The sound of gunfire could be heard from within Aden itself, 
an AFP correspondent said. 
  Al-Jumhuriyah hospital sources said the day's shelling had 
killed six civilians and wounded a further 56, while 13 soldiers 
were also killed and 124 injured. 
  Since June 11, an estimated 415 civilians have been killed 
and more than 1,100 injured in bombardments in and around Aden, 
according to statistics compiled from official and hospital 
sources. 
  A southern military spokesman said meanwhile that southern 
troops had managed to halt "new attempts by enemy forces to 
progress towards Aden." 
  "Four northern tanks were destroyed and hundreds of enemy 
soldiers and officers killed or wounded," the spokesman said, 
while others had been taken prisoner. 
  A southern statement vowed that "Aden will resist and will 
transform itself into a cemetery for the new invaders." 
  An unspecified number of northern aircraft earlier launched 
a 
raid on Aden's oil refinery, 18 kilometres (10 miles) west of 
the city, the southern spokesman said, adding ground defences 
had downed one plane. 
  Eyewitnesses said two planes fired four missiles at the 
refinery, one of which hit an empty building. Another damaged 
pipelines. 
  A spokesman for the north in Sanaa denied its planes had 
launched an air raid. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

